# Spring Boot Standards

## Package Structure
```
controller/   — REST controllers only, no business logic
service/      — Business logic
model/        — Domain/entity classes
repository/   — Data access layer
```

## Controllers
- Annotate with `@RestController` + `@RequestMapping`
- Return `ResponseEntity<T>` for all endpoints
- No business logic — delegate everything to the service layer

```java
// ❌ BAD — logic in controller
@GetMapping("/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<VoltStore> get(@PathVariable Long id) {
    return repository.findById(id)
        .map(ResponseEntity::ok)
        .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
}

// ✅ GOOD — delegate to service
@GetMapping("/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<VoltStore> get(@PathVariable Long id) {
    return ResponseEntity.ok(voltStoreService.getById(id));
}
```

## Services
- Annotate with `@Service`
- One service per domain entity
- All public methods should be the single entry point for business logic

## Models
- Use Lombok: `@Data`, `@Builder`, `@NoArgsConstructor`, `@AllArgsConstructor`
- No business logic inside model classes

## General
- Use constructor injection via `@RequiredArgsConstructor` — never `@Autowired` on fields
- Always add explicit imports — do not rely on wildcard imports
- Use `@Slf4j` for logging; never use `System.out.println`
- Validate input at the controller layer with `@Valid`
